(3168, 'Desarrollo Urbano y Vivienda | Urbanization in Latin America', 'EdX keeps courses open for enrollment after they end to allow learners to explore content and continue learning.', 'EdX keeps courses open for enrollment after they end to allow learners to explore content and continue learning. All features and materials may not be all available. Check back often to see when new course start dates are announced.  AmÃ©rica Latina y el Caribe estÃ¡ viviendo un rÃ¡pido proceso de urbanizaciÃ³n que trae consigo riesgos y oportunidades para el desarrollo integral y sostenible de esta regiÃ³n. Â¿CÃ³mo se puede manejar la expansiÃ³n urbana y planear de manera efectiva? Â¿CÃ³mo se puede asegurar vivienda digna para la creciente poblaciÃ³n? Â¿QuÃ© hacer con el nacimiento acelerado de barrios informales en las ciudades en desarrollo? Â¿CÃ³mo se puede valorizar el patrimonio urbano y revitalizar los centros histÃ³ricos? Este curso pretende dar respuesta a estas preguntas por medio de recursos teÃ³ricos, videos, actividades prÃ¡cticas, lecciones aprendidas y casos de estudio que permitan al participante comprender el contexto urbano de AmÃ©rica Latina y el Caribe. Asimismo, se hace un esfuerzo por conectar a los participantes y sus experiencias y de esta forma dialogar y trabajar en soluciones conjuntas a los problemas a nivel general y particular que enfrenta la RegiÃ³n y sus ciudades. Este MOOC estÃ¡ orientado a funcionarios pÃºblicos de AmÃ©rica Latina y el Caribe que trabajan o estÃ¡n involucrados en el Ã¡mbito de desarrollo urbano y vivienda. Se desarrollÃ³ tambiÃ©n, teniendo en mente a los actores que, a travÃ©s del estudio o su labor cotidiana, estÃ¡n teniendo un mayor acercamiento a esta temÃ¡tica y sus derivaciones. Todos los inscritos tendrÃ¡n la oportunidad de participar en una actividad que les permitirÃ¡ aplicar de forma agregada los contenidos estudiados a lo largo del curso y con base a ello, presentar una intervenciÃ³n urbana de su ciudad. A los autores de los trabajos mÃ¡s destacados se les invitarÃ¡ a exhibirlo en Â¡Viva el Centro! un evento organizado por el Banco Interamericano de Desarrollo. Si tienes alguna pregunta, escrÃ­benos aÂ idbx@iadb.org La preparaciÃ³n de este curso fue financiada por el Programa Especial para el Desarrollo Institucional (SPID) del Banco Interamericano de Desarrollo. Mayor informaciÃ³n en la pÃ¡gina web del SPID. Â  Latin America and the Caribbean region is experiencing a rapid urbanization process that carries risks and opportunities for its integral and sustainable development. How can urban expansion be managed and effectively planned for? How can decent housing be guaranteed for the growing population? As informal settlements in developing cities increase, how does this impact urban planning? How can urban heritage gain value and historic centers be revitalized? This course hopes to provide answers to these questions through theoretical content, videos, hands-on activities, and case studies that will help participants understand the urban context of Latin America and the Caribbean. Likewise, an effort has been made to connect participants and their experiences so that joint solutions can be found for general and specific problems the Region and its cities are facing today. This MOOC is specially targeted at public officials in Latin America and the Caribbean, who work or, directly or indirectly, are involved in urban and housing development. Also, it was thought out for those who, through academic activities or everyday work, are having a greater and deeper contact with these topics and its derivatives. Once registered, you will have the opportunity to participate in an assignment that lets you apply the studied contents as a whole and based on it, and share an urban intervention from your city. The authors of the best work will be invited to present it in Â¡Viva el Centro!-- an event organized by the Inter-American Development Bank .Â  If you have any questions, please contact us atÂ idbx@iadb.org The preparation of this course was financed by the Special Program for Institutional Development (SPID) of the Inter-American Development Bank. For more information visit theÂ SPID website.Â  ', 'https://edx.org/course/desarrollo-urbano-y-vivienda-idbx-idb7x', '', '2015-11-24', 42, '', 'Social Sciences', 'edX', 0, 'EspaÃ±ol', 'yes', 'IDBx', '2015-11-24 23:09:30'),
(3169, 'Design and Development of Educational Technology', 'EdX keeps courses open for enrollment after they end to allow learners to explore content and continue learning.', 'EdX keeps courses open for enrollment after they end to allow learners to explore content and continue learning. All features and materials may not be all available. Check back often to see when new course start dates are announced.  To be effective, educational technologies must be designed based on what we know about how people learn. Through interviews with multiple experts in the field, this course examines educational technologies, outlines the theories that influenced their development, and examines their use. The course leads up to a final project â a kickstarter style pitch for a new educational technology - which is worked on iteratively across the weeks.Â  It involves active weekly participation. In week 1, weâll talk about the history of educational technologies and how they change the way we learn.Â Weâll also discuss two important educational theories that focus on student-centered learning. In week 2, weâll explore what it means to learn something and examine several different approaches to deepen learning. Weâll begin by introducing a specific framework for thinking about learning. Weâll then take a close look at how educational software developers are more deeply engaging learners and even providing feedback to students as they learn. Week 3 will focus on forms of Active Learning, where students choose and pursue activities based on their own interests. Weâll also talk with experts about designing to help build important non-cognitive skills, like persistence and developing mastery. Week 4 will move from individual learning to collaborative learning in a range of forms, from apprenticeships to communities of practice. Weâll speak with experts about the many ways learning in groups can manifest itself. No matter what the medium, collaborative learning has a lot to teach us. Week 5 focuses on assessment. Â All the clever educational technology design in the world isnât very useful if we donât know whether studentsâ learning is being enhanced by it or what changes need to be made to increase its effectiveness.Â Weâll talk with teachers, students, and assessment experts who will provide an overview of the different types of assessment and how technology is changing the field of assessment. Finally, in week 6, weâll talk about design-based research, a methodology for research and design of educational innovations in which you create projects that embody the educational change you wish to study. Week 0 of this course is a ''ramp-up'' week for participants to introduce themselves to one another and become familiar with the forums and other course platform features. ', 'https://edx.org/course/design-development-educational-mitx-11-132x', 'http://www.youtube.com/v/hiU2d0GUN1M?version=3&amp;autohide=1', '2015-11-24', 91, 'https://www.edx.org/sites/default/files/styles/course_video_banner/public/course/image/featured-card/11-132x-design-378x225.jpg?itok=J2cgg84-', 'Computer Science', 'edX', 0, 'English', 'no', 'MITx', '2015-11-24 23:09:30');
