(3000, '"A Christmas Carol" by Dickens: BerkeleyX Book Club', 'This course will explore in depth Charles Dickensâ 1843 novella, âA Christmas Carol,â which has an important place in English language literature.', 'This course will explore in depth Charles Dickensâ 1843 novella, âA Christmas Carol,â which has an important place in English language literature. It has given us enduring characters, such as Scrooge and Tiny Tim, and common sayings, like âBah! Humbug!â. Whether you celebrate Christmas or not, you will find that this book offers important themes, including generosity, poverty, and social injustice. Â  Participants in this course will read, discuss, and write about the text and its influence. As in most book clubs, the focus will be on lively discussion. Course materials will include background information for understanding the text, as well as vocabulary and language support. Assessment will include quizzes and short writing assignments. Â  This is the first part of the BerkeleyX Book Club offerings. ', 'https://edx.org/course/christmas-carol-dickens-berkeleyx-book-uc-berkeleyx-colwri3-1x-0', 'http://www.youtube.com/v/ftvYkwK5Sbg?version=3&amp;autohide=1', '2015-12-01', 28, 'https://www.edx.org/sites/default/files/styles/course_video_banner/public/course/image/featured-card/a_christmas_carol_378x225.jpg?itok=-3194oHC', 'Humanities', 'edX', 0, 'English', 'yes', 'UC BerkeleyX', '2015-11-24 23:09:30'),
(3001, '"A Room with a View" by Forster: BerkeleyX Book Club', 'A Room with a View is a 1908 novel by English writer E.', 'A Room with a View is a 1908 novel by English writer E.M. Forster. Â  A Room with a View is a romance and a critique of English society at the beginning of the 20th century. As Forsterâs most romantic and optimistic book, A Room with a View is considered one of the top 100 English language novels of all times. An award-winning film adaptation of this novel came out in 1985. Participants in this course will read, discuss, and write about the text and its influence. As in most book clubs, the focus will be on lively discussion. Course materials will include background information for understanding the text, as well as vocabulary and language support. Assessment will include quizzes and short writing assignments. ', 'https://edx.org/course/room-view-forster-berkeleyx-book-club-uc-berkeleyx-colwri3-11x', '', '2016-02-03', 28, '', 'Humanities', 'edX', 0, 'English', 'yes', 'UC BerkeleyX', '2015-11-24 23:09:31'),
(3002, '"A Study in Scarlet" by Doyle: BerkeleyX Book Club', 'EdX keeps courses open for enrollment after they end to allow learners to explore content and continue learning.', 'EdX keeps courses open for enrollment after they end to allow learners to explore content and continue learning. All features and materials may not be all available. Check back often to see when new course start dates are announced.  This course will exploreÂ A Study in Scarlet, an 1887 detective mystery novel by Sir Arthur Conan Doyle. This novel introduced the iconic Sherlock Holmes and his friend Dr. John Watson. The book''s title comes from a speech Holmes gives to Doctor Watson about his work, saying: "There''s the scarlet thread of murder running through the colourless skein of life, and our duty is to unravel it, and isolate it, and expose every inch of it." The story received little very public interest when it first appeared. In fact, only eleven complete copies ofÂ Beeton''s Christmas AnnualÂ 1887 are known to exist. Many adaptations of Sherlock Holmes exist, however, and he continues to fascinate readers as an enigmatic detective. Participants in this course will read, discuss, and write about the text and its influence. As in most book clubs, the focus will be on lively discussion. Course materials will include background information for understanding the text, as well as vocabulary and language support. Assessment will include quizzes and short writing assignments. ', 'https://edx.org/course/study-scarlet-doyle-berkeleyx-book-club-uc-berkeleyx-colwri3-8x', '', '2015-11-24', 28, '', 'Humanities', 'edX', 0, 'English', 'yes', 'UC BerkeleyX', '2015-11-24 23:09:31'),
(3003, '"Adventures of Huckleberry Finn" by Twain: BerkeleyX Book Club', 'EdX keeps courses open for enrollment after they end to allow learners to explore content and continue learning.', 'EdX keeps courses open for enrollment after they end to allow learners to explore content and continue learning. All features and materials may not be all available. Check back often to see when new course start dates are announced.  This course will explore in depth Mark Twainâs 1884Â  novel,Â Huckleberry Finn, which has an important place in American literature and history. This novel is among the first in majorÂ American literatureÂ to be written inÂ dialect, characterized by regional Southern English. While this makes the writing difficult to understand at first, it also gives us a window into the language of the time. The story is noted for its colorful descriptions of people and places along theÂ Mississippi River. Set in the American South after the Civil War, this book features a society that has ceased to exist about twenty years prior.Â The Adventures of Huckleberry FinnÂ is often described as aÂ satireÂ on deep-rooted attitudes, particularly racism, in the South. Â  Participants in this course will read, discuss, and write about the text and its influence. As in most book clubs, the focus will be on lively discussion. Course materials will include background information for understanding the text, as well as vocabulary and language support. Assessment will include quizzes and short writing assignments. Â  This is the second part of the BerkeleyX Book Club offerings. ', 'https://edx.org/course/adventures-huckleberry-finn-twain-uc-berkeleyx-colwri3-2x', '', '2015-11-24', 28, '', 'Humanities', 'edX', 0, 'English', 'yes', 'UC BerkeleyX', '2015-11-24 23:09:29'),
(3004, '"Call of the Wild" by London: BerkeleyX Book Club', 'The Call of the Wild is a 1903 novel written by Jack London.', 'The Call of the Wild is a 1903 novel written by Jack London. The story is set in the Yukon, the far northern territory of Canada/Alaska, during the 1890s Klondike Gold Rush. During this period, good sled dogs were in high demand. The novel''s main character is a dog named Buck, who lives on a California ranch. London himself lived nearly a year in the Yukon, collecting material for the novel. Like many older popular novels, The Call of the Wild was serialized in the Saturday Evening Post in the summer of 1903. A month later, it was released as a Â book. The novelâs great popularity and success made London famous. The appeal of this story comes from its simplicity as a tale of survival. As early as 1908, the story was adapted to film. Since then, there have been other adaptations. Participants in this course will read, discuss, and write about the text and its influence. As in most book clubs, the focus will be on lively discussion. Course materials will include background information for understanding the text, as well as vocabulary and language support. Assessment will include quizzes and short writing assignments. ', 'https://edx.org/course/call-wild-london-berkeleyx-book-club-uc-berkeleyx-colwri3-12x', '', '2016-03-01', 28, '', 'Humanities', 'edX', 0, 'English', 'yes', 'UC BerkeleyX', '2015-11-24 23:09:30'),
(3005, '"Dracula" by Stoker: BerkeleyX Book Club', 'EdX keeps courses open for enrollment after they end to allow learners to explore content and continue learning.', 'EdX keeps courses open for enrollment after they end to allow learners to explore content and continue learning. All features and materials may not be all available. Check back often to see when new course start dates are announced.  This course will explore Bram Stokerâs 1897 classic vampire novel, Dracula, which is famous for introducing the vampire Count Dracula. This is the story of Dracula''s move from Transylvania to England to find new blood and spread the curse of the undead. It also introduces the now-famous character of Professor Abraham Van Helsing. The novel Dracula is categorized in many different ways: vampire, horror, and gothic fiction. It also addresses concepts such as women in Victorian culture, colonialism, sexuality, and post-colonialism. Although Stoker was not the first writer to tell the story of a vampire, he is credited for giving the vampire its modern form. This story has been adapted to many different forms in film and theater. Participants in this course will read, discuss, and write about the text and its influence. As in most book clubs, the focus will be on lively discussion. Course materials will include background information for understanding the text, as well as vocabulary and language support. Assessment will include quizzes and short writing assignments. ', 'https://edx.org/course/dracula-stoker-berkeleyx-book-club-uc-berkeleyx-colwri3-6x', '', '2015-11-24', 28, '', 'Humanities', 'edX', 0, 'English', 'yes', 'UC BerkeleyX', '2015-11-24 23:09:30'),
(3006, '"Dubliners" by Joyce: BerkeleyX Book Club', 'EdX keeps courses open for enrollment after they end to allow learners to explore content and continue learning.', 'EdX keeps courses open for enrollment after they end to allow learners to explore content and continue learning. All features and materials may not be all available. Check back often to see when new course start dates are announced.  This course will examine James Joyceâs collection of fifteen short stories called simplyÂ Dubliners. This volume was first published in 1914, but not without a struggle. Joyce first submitted these stories to a publisher in 1905, and had it rejected 17 times before it was finally published in 1914. It has become one of the classics of English language literature, despite its rocky beginnings. DublinersÂ depicts middle class Irish life in the early part of the 20th century. The first stories are narrated by protagonists who are children. As the stories continue, they examine the lives of characters in increasingly older stages of life. Interestingly, many of the characters who appear in these short stories appear later in minor roles in Joyceâs famous novelÂ Ulysses. Â  Participants in this course will read, discuss, and write about the text and its influence. As in most book clubs, the focus will be on lively discussion. Course materials will include background information for understanding the text, as well as vocabulary and language support. Assessment will include quizzes and short writing assignments. Â  This is the fifth part of the BerkeleyX Book Club offerings. ', 'https://edx.org/course/dubliners-joyce-berkeleyx-book-club-uc-berkeleyx-colwri3-5x', '', '2015-11-24', 28, '', 'Humanities', 'edX', 0, 'English', 'yes', 'UC BerkeleyX', '2015-11-24 23:09:30'),
(3007, '"Frankenstein; Or, The Modern Prometheus" by Shelley: BerkeleyX Book Club', 'EdX keeps courses open for enrollment after they end to allow learners to explore content and continue learning.', 'EdX keeps courses open for enrollment after they end to allow learners to explore content and continue learning. All features and materials may not be all available. Check back often to see when new course start dates are announced.  This course will explore Mary Wollstonecraft Shelleyâs 1818 horror classic,Â Frankenstein; Or, The Modern Prometheus. This novel is remarkable for a number of reasons, not the least of which is that Shelley wrote the novel when she was only 18 years old. FrankensteinÂ is a representation of both the Gothic and Romantic movements, and is often considered to be one of the earliest novels of science fiction as well. This story has had a huge influence on literature and popular culture, and has generated many adaptations in the forms of movies and plays.Â  The first film adaptation, in fact, appeared in 1910. Participants in this course will read, discuss, and write about the text and its influence. As in most book clubs, the focus will be on lively discussion. Course materials will include background information for understanding the text, as well as vocabulary and language support. Assessment will include quizzes and short writing assignments. Â  This is the third part of the BerkeleyX Book Club offerings. ', 'https://edx.org/course/frankenstein-or-modern-prometheus-uc-berkeleyx-colwri3-3x', 'http://www.youtube.com/v/jp7Vs8DHXR4?version=3&amp;autohide=1', '2015-11-24', 28, 'https://www.edx.org/sites/default/files/styles/course_video_banner/public/course/image/featured-card/frankenstein_378x225.jpg?itok=P5MG_6lF', 'Humanities', 'edX', 0, 'English', 'no', 'UC BerkeleyX', '2015-11-24 23:09:31'),
(3008, '"Jane Eyre" by Bronte: BerkeleyX Book Club', 'Jane Eyre is a novel by English writer Charlotte BrontÃ«.', 'Jane Eyre is a novel by English writer Charlotte BrontÃ«. It was published in 1847 under her pen name, Currer Bell. Jane Eyre is often referred to as a bildungsroman, or coming-of-age story. It follows the feelings and experiences of the protagonist and title character, Jane Eyre, from youth to adulthood.Â  The story has both elements of social criticism as well as a strong moral core. Many critics have considered this book to be ahead of its time, mostly due to Janeâs individualism, as well as story themes that include classism, sexuality, religion, and feminism. Participants in this course will read, discuss, and write about the text and its influence. As in most book clubs, the focus will be on lively discussion. Course materials will include background information for understanding the text, as well as vocabulary and language support. Assessment will include quizzes and short writing assignments. ', 'https://edx.org/course/jane-eyre-bronte-berkeleyx-book-club-uc-berkeleyx-colwri3-10x', '', '2016-01-04', 28, '', 'Humanities', 'edX', 0, 'English', 'yes', 'UC BerkeleyX', '2015-11-24 23:09:31'),
(3009, '"Pride and Prejudice" by Austen: BerkeleyX Book Club', 'This course will explore Jane Austenâs 1813 novel of manners,Â Â Pride and Prejudice.', 'This course will explore Jane Austenâs 1813 novel of manners,Â Â Pride and Prejudice. Although the story of the Bennet sisters takes place at the turn of the 19th century, it still fascinates modern readers. One of the most popular books in the English language,Â Pride and PrejudiceÂ consistently placing near the top of lists of "most loved books." Modern interest in the book has resulted in a number of adaptations for film and stage--since 1940, there have been four TV and movie versions of this book, as well as a plethora of spin-off books, includingÂ Bridget Jones'' DiaryÂ andÂ Pride and Prejudice and Zombies. Participants in this course will read, discuss, and write about the text and its influence. As in most book clubs, the focus will be on lively discussion. Course materials will include background information for understanding the text, as well as vocabulary and language support. Assessment will include quizzes and short writing assignments. ', 'https://edx.org/course/pride-prejudice-austen-berkeleyx-book-uc-berkeleyx-colwri3-9-x', '', '2015-11-02', 28, '', 'Humanities', 'edX', 0, 'English', 'yes', 'UC BerkeleyX', '2015-11-24 23:09:31'),
(3010, '"The Jungle" by Sinclair: BerkeleyX Book Club', 'EdX keeps courses open for enrollment after they end to allow learners to explore content and continue learning.', 'EdX keeps courses open for enrollment after they end to allow learners to explore content and continue learning. All features and materials may not be all available. Check back often to see when new course start dates are announced.  This course will explore Upton Sinclairâs 1906 novel The Jungle, which portrays the exploitation of immigrants in the industrial USA of the early 20th century. However, this novel is most remembered for its depiction of health violations and unclean conditions in the American meatpacking industry. These findings were based on an investigation Sinclair did as a journalist..Â  Sinclair spent several weeks gathering information while working in the meatpacking plants of the Chicago stockyards for the newspaper Appeal to Reason. The Jungle was first published in serial form in 1905 in the newspaper. A film version of the novel was made in 1914, but it has been lost. The novel highlights working class poverty, the lack of social support, harsh living and working conditions, and a bleak outlook for the working poor. This is contrasted with the corruption of those in power. Participants in this course will read, discuss, and write about the text and its influence. As in most book clubs, the focus will be on lively discussion. Course materials will include background information for understanding the text, as well as vocabulary and language support. Assessment will include quizzes and short writing assignments. ', 'https://edx.org/course/jungle-sinclair-berkeleyx-book-club-uc-berkeleyx-colwri3-7x', '', '2015-11-24', 28, '', 'Humanities', 'edX', 0, 'English', 'yes', 'UC BerkeleyX', '2015-11-24 23:09:31'),
(3011, '"The Picture of Dorian Gray" by Wilde: BerkeleyX Book Club', 'This course will examine Oscar Wildeâs only novel,Â The Picture of Dorian Gray.', 'This course will examine Oscar Wildeâs only novel,Â The Picture of Dorian Gray. This novel was first published as a serial novel inÂ Lippincottâs Monthly MagazineÂ in 1890. The Picture of Dorian GrayÂ was immediately controversial, and was censored by the magazineâs editors. Even with the censorship, reviewers still thought that Wilde ought to have been prosecuted for violating laws concerning public morality. This story has two important themes: the idea of selling oneâs soul, and the theme of living a double life. Wilde takes these themes to their extreme. Â  Participants in this course will read, discuss, and write about the text and its influence. As in most book clubs, the focus will be on lively discussion. Course materials will include background information for understanding the text, as well as vocabulary and language support. Assessment will include quizzes and short writing assignments. Â  This is the fourth part of the BerkeleyX Book Club offerings. ', 'https://edx.org/course/picture-dorian-gray-wilde-berkeleyx-book-uc-berkeleyx-colwri3-4x', '', '2016-04-01', 28, '', 'Humanities', 'edX', 0, 'English', 'yes', 'UC BerkeleyX', '2015-11-24 23:09:31'),
(3012, '3D Opportunity: Additive Manufacturing for Business Leaders', 'Aimed at a general business audience, this course provides an overview of a wide range of additive manufacturing technologies and offers a framework to help learners understand the business implications of these technologies.', 'Aimed at a general business audience, this course provides an overview of a wide range of additive manufacturing technologies and offers a framework to help learners understand the business implications of these technologies. The course is relevant for professionals working in product design, manufacturing, supply chain, strategy, and other disciplines. Through the course, participants will build a knowledge base on additive manufacturing to help them engage in discussions with colleagues, customers, and suppliers about how the technology applies to their business.', 'https://novoed.com/3d-opportunity-2015', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/AtM704ehhI8?vq=auto&rel=0&showinfo=0&autohide=1&wmode=transparent&origin=https://novoed.com', '2015-02-09', 48, '', '', 'NovoEd', -1, 'English', 'no', 'Deloitte University Press', '2015-11-24 23:09:29'),
(3013, 'A Global History of Architecture', 'How do we understand architecture?', 'How do we understand architecture? One way of answering this question is by looking through the lens of history, beginning with First Societies and extending to the 16th century. This course in architectural history is not intended as a linear narrative, but rather aims to provide a more global view, by focusing on different architectural "moments." How did the introduction of iron in the ninth century BCE impact regional politics and the development of architecture? How did new religious formations, such as Buddhism and Hinduism, produce new architectural understandings? What were the architectural consequences of the changing political landscape in northern Italy in the 14th century? How did rock-cut architecture move across space and time from West Asia to India to Africa? How did the emergence of corn impact the rise of religious and temple construction in Mexico? Each lecture analyzes a particular architectural transformation arising from a dynamic cultural situation. Material covered in lectures will be supplemented by readings from the textbook A Global History of Architecture. Join us on a journey around the globe and learn how architecture has developed and interacted with the worldâs culture, religion, and history. ', 'https://edx.org/course/global-history-architecture-mitx-4-605x3', 'http://www.youtube.com/v/1SzigQy2SWU?version=3&amp;autohide=1', '2015-09-22', 84, 'https://www.edx.org/sites/default/files/styles/course_video_banner/public/course/image/featured-card/4065x_378x225_0.jpg?itok=A9xcoc_c', 'History', 'edX', 0, 'English', 'yes', 'MITx', '2015-11-24 23:09:31'),
(3014, 'A System View of Communications: From Signals to Packets (Part 1)', 'EdX keeps courses open for enrollment after they end to allow learners to explore content and continue learning.', 'EdX keeps courses open for enrollment after they end to allow learners to explore content and continue learning. All features and materials may not be all available. Check back often to see when new course start dates are announced.  Have you ever wondered how information is transmitted using your mobile phone or a WiFi hotspot? This introductory course seeks to enable you to understand the basic engineering tools used and tradeoffs encountered in the design of these communication systems. Â  This course is divided into three parts. In Part 1, we examine the point-to-point link, which communicates information from a single transmitter to a single receiver.Â Part 2 examines how multiple transmitters can share the same physical channel. Part 3 discusses how information can be transmitted reliably from one station to another over a network that connects multiple stations.Â Online interactive exercises are included to help build your intuition. This course was inspired by and built upon the course 6.02 Digital Communication Systems developed at MIT, which Prof Bertram Shi worked on during his sabbatical in 2009. ', 'https://edx.org/course/system-view-communications-signals-hkustx-elec1200-1x-0', 'http://www.youtube.com/v/Hy2xlbL2xaQ?version=3&amp;autohide=1', '2015-11-24', 49, 'https://www.edx.org/sites/default/files/styles/course_video_banner/public/course/image/featured-card/hkustx-elec1200.x-378x225.png?itok=Dc1zOnO8', 'Computer Science', 'edX', 0, 'English', 'yes', 'HKUSTx', '2015-11-24 23:09:31'),
