(3099, 'Career Edge: Resume, Networking and Interview Skills', 'With only a small window of opportunity to make a lasting impression on prospective employers, what should you do to get noticed?', 'With only a small window of opportunity to make a lasting impression on prospective employers, what should you do to get noticed? This career development course prepares you to reach out to desired organizations, succeed in your interview, and then excel on the job. Use self-assessments and interactive exercises to help you build a standout resume that will get you noticed. Using simulations, youâll learn interview preparation techniques that will enable you to ace the interview and start your career journey.Â  This is the fifth course in the five-part Career Edge Fullbridge XSeries, designed to prepare you for career success. ', 'https://edx.org/course/career-edge-resume-networking-interview-fullbridgex-career5x', '', '2015-11-24', 28, '', 'Business & Management', 'edX', 0, 'English', 'yes', 'FullbridgeX', '2015-11-24 23:09:30'),
(3100, 'Cellular Mechanisms of Brain Function', 'EdX keeps courses open for enrollment after they end to allow learners to explore content and continue learning.', 'EdX keeps courses open for enrollment after they end to allow learners to explore content and continue learning. All features and materials may not be all available. Check back often to see when new course start dates are announced.  Brain and behavior are inextricably linked in neuroscience. The function of the brain is to govern behavior, and the aim of this course is to causally link biophysical mechanisms with simple behaviors studied in mice. The brain processes information through the concerted activity of many neurons, which communicate with each other through synapses organised in highly dynamic networks. The first goal of the course is to gain a detailed understanding of the structure and function of the fundamental building blocks of the mammalian brain, its synapses and neurons. The second goal is to understand neuronal networks, with specific emphasis on the interactions of excitatory glutamatergic and inhibitory GABAergic neurons. The third goal is to place neuronal network function in the context of sensory processing ultimately leading to behavioral decisions and motor output. ', 'https://edx.org/course/cellular-mechanisms-brain-function-epflx-brainx-0', 'http://www.youtube.com/v/RJUsTzwziuI?version=3&amp;autohide=1', '2015-11-24', 56, 'https://www.edx.org/sites/default/files/styles/course_video_banner/public/course/image/featured-card/cellular-mechanisms-of-brain-function_378x225.jpg?itok=3eiVQXDN', 'Biology & Life Sciences', 'edX', 0, 'English', 'yes', 'EPFLx', '2015-11-24 23:09:30'),
(3101, 'Central Challenges of American National Security, Strategy, and the Press', 'EdX keeps courses open for enrollment after they end to allow learners to explore content and continue learning.', 'EdX keeps courses open for enrollment after they end to allow learners to explore content and continue learning. All features and materials may not be all available. Check back often to see when new course start dates are announced.  This course is set to Open-Archived mode. You may register for this course and peruse the content at your own pace, but at this time you may not pursue a certificate. How can Iran be stopped from getting a nuclear bombânegotiations, sanctions, or military action? As a participant in this course, you will advise the president in deciding whether, and how, the U.S. should act. Once youâve made your assessment, you will move on to wrestle with other scenarios preoccupying policy makers. Between the Assad regime and ISIS, civilians in Syria and Iraq face unimaginable atrocities. Should the U.S. intervene? Chinaâs rise is rattling capitalist economies and a half-century of Pacific peace. What counterbalancing actions should Washington take? Leaks are a fact of life â but why do they happen? Who gets them, and why? Should journalists publish or withhold them? Does legal accountability lie with the leakerâor the journalist? This six-week course casts you as advisors on the hardest decisions any president has to make. We will go behind the veil to see the dynamic between the press and the U.S. government, to explore these dilemmas. We will also have to contend with the reality that government secrets rarely stay that way. Participants will learn to navigate the political landscape of an era in which private remarks become viral tweets, and mistakes by intelligence agencies become front-page stories. Weekly assignments require strategic thinking: Analyzing dynamics of challenges and developing strategies for addressing them.Â  Students wi