(3107, 'Chinaâs Perspective on Climate Change | åºå¯¹æ°åååçä¸­å½è§è§', 'This course provides Chinaâs perspective on global climate change.', 'This course provides Chinaâs perspective on global climate change. Learn about Chinaâs view of the scientific basis of climate change, the challenges and impact it has on regional climate in China, and the adaptation and mitigation measuresÂ for addressing it. Chinaâs climate policies and actions will be presented as well as an interpretation of Chinaâs Intended Nationally Determined Contributions (INDC) and the co-benefits of ambitious climate actions relating to energy security, environmental protection and sustainable development. Special note: This course will be available during the 21st session of the Conference of the Parties to the UNFCCC (COP 21), known as the 2015 Paris Climate Conference. ', 'https://edx.org/course/chinas-perspective-climate-change-ying-tsinghuax-00460032x', '', '2015-11-23', 70, '', 'Energy & Earth Sciences', 'edX', 0, 'English', 'yes', 'TsinghuaX', '2015-11-24 23:09:30'),
(3108, 'Chinese Thought: Ancient Wisdom Meets Modern Science - Part 1', 'EdX keeps courses open for enrollment after they end to allow learners to explore content and continue learning.', 'EdX keeps courses open for enrollment after they end to allow learners to explore content and continue learning. All features and materials may not be all available. Check back often to see when new course start dates are announced.  This course is designed to give students a thorough introduction to early (pre-221 BCE) Chinese thought, its contemporary implications, and the role of religion in human well-being. Important themes to be discussed include the ideal of wu-wei or âeffortless action,â the paradox of how one can consciously try not to try, mindfulness techniques and self-cultivation, models of the self and society, rationality versus emotions, trust and human cooperation, and the structure and impact of different spiritual and political ideals. This period of Chinese history witnessed the formation of all of the major indigenous schools of Chinese thought (Confucianism, Daoism, Mohism and Legalism), which in turn had an impact on the development of East Asian cultural history that is still felt today. We will also explore parallels with Western philosophical and religious traditions, the relevance of early Chinese thought for contemporary debates in ethics, moral education, and political philosophy, and the manner in which early Chinese models of the self anticipate recent developments in the evolutionary and cognitive sciences. This course provides a full university semesterâs worth of material broken into two parts. Each part of the course will last 5 weeks, with a week-long break in between.Â For each part, there will be four weeks worth of new material.Â The fifth week will be reserved for review and completion of the final exam. Part 1 introduces the basic philosophical, religious and scientific concepts that will be drawn upon throughout the course, and then goes on to cover early Shang and Zhou religious thought, the Analects of Confucius, the Daodejing (a Daoist text attributed to Laozi), the utilitarian thinker Mozi, the newly discovered and very exciting Guodian texts, and the momentous philosophical changes that occurred in the mid Warring States period. Â  See also: Chinese Thought: Ancient Wisdom Meets Modern Science - Part 2 ', 'https://edx.org/course/chinese-thought-ancient-wisdom-meets-ubcx-china300-1x', 'http://www.youtube.com/v/BkSs2URfWuI?version=3&amp;autohide=1', '2015-11-24', 35, 'https://www.edx.org/sites/default/files/styles/course_video_banner/public/course/image/featured-card/china300.1x-chinese_thought-378x225b.png?itok=8ETU3iX5', 'Art & Culture', 'edX', 0, 'English', 'yes', 'UBCx', '2015-11-24 23:09:30'),
(3109, 'Chinese Thought: Ancient Wisdom Meets Modern Science - Part 2', 'This course is designed to give students a thorough introduction to early (pre-221 BCE) Chinese thought, its contemporary implications, and the role of religion in human well-being.', 'This course is designed to give students a thorough introduction to early (pre-221 BCE) Chinese thought, its contemporary implications, and the role of religion in human well-being. Important themes to be discussed include the ideal of wu-wei or âeffortless action,â the paradox of how one can consciously try not to try, mindfulness techniques and self-cultivation, models of the self and society, rationality versus emotions, trust and human cooperation, and the structure and impact of different spiritual and political ideals. This period of Chinese history witnessed the formation of all of the major indigenous schools of Chinese thought (Confucianism, Daoism, Mohism and Legalism), which in turn had an impact on the development of East Asian cultural history that is still felt today. We will also explore parallels with Western philosophical and religious traditions, the relevance of early Chinese thought for contemporary debates in ethics, moral education, and political philosophy, and the manner in which early Chinese models of the self anticipate recent developments in the evolutionary and cognitive sciences. This course provides a full university semesterâs worth of material broken into two parts. Each part of the course will last five weeks with a week-long break in between.Â For each part, there will be four weeks worth of new material.Â The fifth week will be reserved for review and completion of the final exam. Part 2 builds upon Part 1 by exploring late Warring States thinkers such as the Confucian Mencius, the Daoist Zhuangzi, and the return to externalism in the form of Xunziâwho believed Mencius betrayed the original Confucian visionâand his former student Hanfeizi, a âLegalistâ thinker who helped lay the foundations for the autocratic system that unified the Warring States into Chinaâs first empire. We will conclude with some reflections on what it means to study religious thought, and the thought of other cultures, in a modern, globalized world. Part 2 can be taken as a stand-alone course, but will be more comprehensible and rewarding with the background provided in Part 1. See also: Chinese Thought: Ancient Wisdom Meets Modern Science - Part 1 ', 'https://edx.org/course/chinese-thought-ancient-wisdom-meets-ubcx-china300-2x', 'http://www.youtube.com/v/BkSs2URfWuI?version=3&amp;autohide=1', '2015-10-26', 35, 'https://www.edx.org/sites/default/files/styles/course_video_banner/public/course/image/featured-card/china300.2x-chinese_thought-378x225b.png?itok=CWFcEwfs', 'Art & Culture', 'edX', 0, 'English', 'yes', 'UBCx', '2015-11-24 23:09:30'),
(3110, 'Circuits and Electronics 1: Basic Circuit Analysis', 'Want to learn about circuits and electronics, but unsure where to begin?', 'Want to learn about circuits and electronics, but unsure where to begin? Wondering how to make computers run faster or your mobile phone battery last longer? This free circuit course taught by edX CEO and MIT Professor Anant Agarwal and colleagues is for you. This is the first of three online Circuits & Electronics courses offered by Professor Anant Agarwal and colleagues at MIT, and is taken by all MIT Electrical Engineering and Computer Science (EECS) majors. Topics covered include: resistive elements and networks; circuit analysis methods including KVL, KCL and the node method; independent and dependent sources; linearity, superposition, Thevenin & Norton methods; digital abstraction, combinational gates; and MOSFET switches and small signal analysis. Design and lab exercises are also significant components of the course. Weekly coursework includes interactive video sequences, readings from the textbook, homework, online laboratories, and optional tutorials. The course will also have a final exam.Â  This a self-paced course, so there are no weekly deadlines. However, all assignments are due by May 12, 2016, when the course will close. Student Testimonials âBrilliant course! It''s definitely the best introduction to electronics in Universe! Interesting material, clean explanations, well prepared quizzes, challenging homeworks and fun labs.â - Ilya â6.002x will be a classic in the field of online learning. It combines Prof. Agarwal''s enthusiasm for electronics and education. The online circuit design program works very well. The material is difficult. I took the knowledge from the class and built an electronic cat feeder.âÂ - Stan. ', 'https://edx.org/course/circuits-electronics-1-basic-circuit-mitx-6-002-1x', 'http://www.youtube.com/v/zVsStU3dtcw?version=3&amp;autohide=1', '2015-11-24', 35, 'https://www.edx.org/sites/de